Australian, N.Z. Stocks: BHP, Karoon, News Corp., Santos, Toll

-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 
2011-09-19T06:56:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-19/australian-n-z-stocks-bhp-gunns-karoon-news-corp-santos.html
Australia ’s S&P/ASX 200 Index fell
1.6 percent to 4,081.50 at the 4:10 p.m. close of trading  in
Sydney.  New Zealand ’s  NZX 50 Index (NZSE50FG)  slid 0.1 percent to 3,288.31 at
the 5 p.m. close in Wellington. A report today from Westpac
Banking Corp. and McDermott Miller Ltd. showed New Zealand
consumer confidence was unchanged in the third quarter.  The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  Mining companies: A measure of primary metals traded in
 London  fell 0.4 percent on Sept. 16, while copper futures for
December delivery declined 0.6 percent on the Comex in  New York .
Today, New York-traded copper sank as much as 2.2 percent.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  , the world’s No. 1 mining
company, lost 1.7 percent to A$37.60. Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU),
the world’s second-largest mining company by sales, declined 1.5
percent to A$70.20.  Oil stocks: Crude oil for October delivery dropped 1.6
percent on the  New York Mercantile Exchange  on Sept. 16, and as
much as 1.6 percent today.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd. (WPL)  , Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, declined 2.5 percent to A$33.40.
 Santos Ltd. (STO)  , Australia’s third-largest oil and gas
producer, slipped 1.8 percent to A$11.25.  Gold producers: Gold futures for December delivery rose 1.9
percent on the Comex in New York on Sept. 16, and as much as 1
percent today.  Newcrest Mining Ltd. (NCM)  , Australia’s biggest gold
producer, gained 0.2 percent to A$38.17. St. Barbara Ltd. (SBM
AU) added 3.2 percent to A$2.27.        Karoon Gas Australia Ltd. (KAR)   dropped 7.4 percent to
A$2.90. The natural-gas explorer said its Bonaparte Permit AC/P8
venture was unable to identify a prospect that would represent a
viable drilling target. Karoon and venture partner Talisman Oil
& Gas (Australia) Pty are seeking to surrender their exploration
permit immediately, the company said in a Sept. 16 stock-
exchange announcement.        News Corp. (NWSA)   rose 1.5 percent to A$16.20. Shine
Group Ltd., Elisabeth Murdoch’s TV-production company and a unit
of  News Corp. (NWS) , said it bought London-based startup Bossa
Studios, which launched its debut title, Monstermind, on
Facebook Inc.’s gaming platform on Sept. 16. The game involves
players designing and building virtual cities that they defend
against monsters.        Toll Holdings Ltd. (TOL)   lost 0.9 percent to A$4.45.
Australia’s biggest transport company is looking to make
acquisitions to boost its U.S. supply-chain logistics business,
Managing Director Paul Little said in an interview with the Wall
Street Journal.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shani Raja in Sydney at 
